It is a trial and error process, don't get too stress. Don't buy expensive plants if you are not sure if it will survive, because it will be stressful.

If you are in high latitudes, getting a grow light for winter can help if you have tropical plants. Some plants go dormant in winter, they are not dead, just hibernating, they will come back in summer. Read or watch for how to store them during winter.

r/plants r/plantclinic is a good place to learn about plants, common plant issues, pests and ask for help. Knowing the common issues can help you identify pests, root rott, over or under watering. Learn from others mistakes to safe your plant children.

Before attempting to repott or fertilize, watch some videos or read what the type of plant you have likes in terms of substrate and frequency. How to treat the roots and how bigger the new pot should be (usually 2" more at least but not more than 5")

Look at them regularly, not only to admire their beauty but you will get to know them, most plants tell you when they are thirsty or the light is not right. By looking at them regularly you will pick up the changes in the leafs. This is more important for tricky plants.

If you are buying new plants:
🚩🚩 check them thoroughly for pests before getting it home!  you don't want to get pests home.
🚩🚩If you have animals at home and they bite plants check if they are toxic. Some are toxic even without touching, looking at you Lilly. CAREFUL.

Every new plant you buy (better if before), read about her, what type it is, how much light and water they need so you find if is a fit and where in your home to locate it. You might need to try different spots with some.  (Planterina in IG or YT is gold)

Begin with easy ones once a week watering plants. Put an alarm or reminder the day you will water them, so you don't forget (I still have one). Then also have a second day to check on them, for pests, repotting, dry leaves, general happiness.
